Analysis summary for ds001_nsclc

I analyzed 50,000 NSCLC patient records with 73 de-identified features and one outcome, pfs_months. The mean pfs_months was 3.432 months (SD 2.233). I treated binary variables as two-group contrasts, multi-level variables as categorical contrasts, continuous variables with OLS slopes, and then followed the strongest main effects into adjusted and interaction models.

The strongest main-effect pattern was feature_036. Mean pfs_months was 4.327 for feature_036=0, 3.185 for feature_036=1, and 2.152 for feature_036=2; the level 0 vs level 2 contrast was +2.175 months (p<1e-15). This effect remained large after adjustment: feature_036=0 was +2.178 months and feature_036=1 was +1.031 months relative to feature_036=2 in the full main-effect model.

Several other main effects were large and robust. feature_001=1 was associated with markedly lower pfs_months (-1.438 months unadjusted, -1.417 months fully adjusted; p<1e-15). feature_042=1 was also adverse (-0.921 months unadjusted, -0.912 adjusted; p<1e-15). feature_015=adenocarcinoma had higher pfs_months than feature_015=squamous (+0.857 months unadjusted; +0.723 months adjusted; p<1e-15). For feature_025, current had the lowest mean pfs_months (2.987), while former and never were higher (3.607 and 3.675); never vs current was +0.687 months (p<1e-15), and former/never remained about +0.55 months in the full model.

Continuous feature_041 was one of the clearest positive predictors. Its adjusted slope was +0.168 months per unit (p<1e-15). Continuous feature_056 was also positive (+0.463 months per unit adjusted; p<1e-15). Continuous feature_004 was consistently adverse (-0.073 months per unit adjusted; p<1e-15). feature_051 had a statistically significant but very small negative slope. Additional smaller effects included feature_009=1 (+0.323 months adjusted; p<1e-15), feature_037=1 (-0.203 months adjusted; p<1e-15), and feature_029=1 (-0.110 months adjusted; p=7.59e-9).

Some apparent univariate effects did not survive adjustment. feature_028=1 was lower in the unadjusted screen (-0.190 months), but after adjustment the coefficient was only -0.009 months (p=0.243). feature_057=1 looked strongly adverse unadjusted (-0.810 months), but the full main-effect coefficient was -0.028 months (p=0.0629). This suggests its marginal association is largely explained by other covariates, although it remains important in interactions. feature_023 was essentially null in the univariate screen (+0.009 months; p=0.741).

The most clinically meaningful heterogeneity involved feature_010, feature_009, feature_037, and feature_057. feature_010=1 had a positive main association (+0.782 months), but this was concentrated in specific subgroups. The feature_010 by feature_009 interaction was strongly positive: patients with both features had mean pfs_months 5.766, compared with 3.213 for feature_010=1/feature_009=0, 3.329 for feature_010=0/feature_009=1, and 3.334 for neither; the difference-in-differences was +2.558 months (p<1e-15). In contrast, feature_037 strongly attenuated the feature_010 association: the interaction was -1.694 months (p<1e-15). feature_057 also attenuated or reversed the feature_010 association, with a -1.210 month interaction (p<1e-15).

feature_009 showed similar subgroup dependence. Its positive association was present when feature_037=0 but absent when feature_037=1, producing a -0.562 month interaction (p<1e-15). The feature_057 by feature_009 interaction was also negative (-0.488 months; p=4.12e-7). These patterns indicate that the favorable feature_009/feature_010 signal is not uniform across the cohort and is reduced in feature_037- or feature_057-positive subgroups.

Continuous-effect heterogeneity was smaller in magnitude but statistically clear. The positive feature_041 slope was weaker when feature_001=1 than when feature_001=0: +0.1650 vs +0.1776 months per unit, interaction -0.0126 (p<1e-15). feature_004 also weakened the feature_041 association in a centered continuous interaction model, with an interaction coefficient of -0.00074 (p=8.30e-6).

Overall, the dataset contains both strong main-effect structure and notable subgroup heterogeneity. The most robust favorable patterns were feature_036=0/1 vs 2, feature_010=1 in the right subgroup, feature_009=1 in selected subgroups, higher feature_041, higher feature_056, feature_015=adenocarcinoma, and non-current feature_025. The most robust adverse patterns were feature_001=1, feature_042=1, higher feature_004, feature_037=1, and feature_029=1. The largest interaction was the synergistic feature_010 plus feature_009 pattern, while feature_037 and feature_057 identified subgroups where otherwise favorable feature_010/feature_009 associations were markedly blunted.

 succeeded in 1175ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc contained 50,000 patients, 73 opaque features, and the continuous outcome pfs_months. I treated the analysis as exploratory because the feature labels are de-identified. Effects below are signed on the pfs_months scale and p-values are not multiplicity-adjusted.

The strongest main effect was feature_041. In simple OLS, each 1-unit increase in feature_041 was associated with +0.1699 months of PFS (p < 1e-300), and the all-feature adjusted coefficient was nearly identical at +0.1684 months. Feature_036 was also dominant: mean PFS declined from 4.3268 months at feature_036=0 to 3.1854 at feature_036=1 and 2.1519 at feature_036=2. The adjusted feature_036=2 versus 0 coefficient was -2.1775 months (p < 1e-300).

Several binary and categorical main effects were robust. Feature_001=1 was associated with lower PFS both unadjusted (-1.4375 months) and adjusted (-1.4168 months). Feature_042=1 was similarly negative (unadjusted -0.9207, adjusted -0.9122 months). Feature_015=squamous was lower than adenocarcinoma by -0.8569 months unadjusted and -0.7229 months adjusted. Feature_025 former and never categories were favorable relative to current; adjusted coefficients were +0.5517 and +0.5453 months, respectively. Feature_004 was independently negative (-0.0732 months per unit), and feature_056 was independently positive (+0.4630 months per unit). Feature_051 had a statistically detectable but small negative adjusted effect (-0.00045 months per unit).

Some unadjusted findings were screening artifacts. Feature_057=1 looked strongly negative unadjusted (-0.8104 months), but after all-feature adjustment its coefficient was only -0.0283 months and not significant at 0.05 (p=0.0629). Feature_028 and feature_066 also disappeared after adjustment, with adjusted effects of -0.0054 months (p=0.471) and -0.0007 months (p=0.949). This suggests their marginal associations were largely explained by the dominant covariates.

The most clinically meaningful heterogeneity involved feature_010, feature_009, and feature_037. Feature_010=1 was favorable overall (+0.7815 months unadjusted; +0.8924 months adjusted), and feature_009=1 was also favorable (+0.3220 months unadjusted; +0.3231 months adjusted). But their joint effect was much larger than additive: the adjusted feature_010:feature_009 interaction was +2.5406 months (p < 1e-300). Stratified analysis confirmed this: within feature_009=1, feature_010=1 was associated with +2.4372 months, while within feature_009=0 the feature_010 difference was slightly negative (-0.1206 months).

Feature_037 sharply modified those relationships. The adjusted feature_037:feature_010 interaction was -1.6239 months, and feature_037:feature_009 was -0.5843 months. Within feature_037=0, feature_010=1 was associated with +1.5424 months and feature_009=1 with +0.5709 months. Within feature_037=1, feature_010=1 was slightly negative (-0.1517 months) and feature_009=1 was essentially null (+0.0086 months, p=0.771). The three-way interaction feature_037:feature_010:feature_009 was -4.5767 months (p < 1e-300), meaning the large feature_010/feature_009 synergy was concentrated in feature_037=0 patients. The subgroup feature_037=0, feature_010=1, feature_009=1 had mean PFS 7.8760 months versus 3.3188 months in all other patients, a +4.5572 month difference.

Additional interaction checks found smaller heterogeneity. Feature_057 weakened the feature_010 association, with adjusted feature_010:feature_057 interaction -0.8797 months. Feature_036 attenuated the negative effects of feature_001 and feature_042: the feature_036=2 interaction increments were +0.2309 months for feature_001 and +0.1705 months for feature_042. Feature_041 stayed positive at all feature_036 levels, but its slope weakened from +0.1790 months per unit at feature_036=0 to +0.1464 at feature_036=2. Feature_015=squamous slightly attenuated the feature_001 effect (+0.0743 month interaction), but it did not modify the feature_010:feature_009 synergy (interaction +0.0149, p=0.587). Feature_025 also did not strongly modify that synergy; the former category interaction was null and the never category was statistically negative but small relative to the base synergy.

In the all-feature adjusted model, the dominant signals were feature_041, feature_036, feature_001, feature_042, feature_015, feature_010, feature_004, feature_056, feature_025, feature_009, and feature_037. Remaining independent signals were small: feature_029=-0.1095 months, feature_048=-0.0292 months, and feature_023=-0.0192 months. Weak continuous markers such as feature_013 and feature_070 were not significant after full adjustment. Overall, the data support a strong multivariable structure with both large baseline-like main effects and a highly specific feature_010-feature_009-feature_037 interaction pattern in PFS.

 succeeded in 1222ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc contains 50000 NSCLC patient records with 73 opaque feature columns, patient_id, and the outcome pfs_months. I analyzed pfs_months as a continuous outcome using unadjusted mean comparisons or simple OLS, then multivariable OLS with all available feature columns encoded as numeric terms or categorical dummies. P-values use large-sample normal approximations for coefficients and Welch-style mean differences.

The outcome had mean 3.432 months, SD 2.233 months, median 3.319, and interquartile range 1.755 to 4.896 months.

Main-effect findings:
- feature_041 showed a supported positive association: 1.699 months per 10 units unadjusted (p<1e-300) and 1.684 months per 10 units adjusted (p<1e-300).
- feature_025 showed supported favorable differences for never and former versus current: never-current 0.687 months (p<1e-300), former-current 0.620 months (p<1e-300), with adjusted never-current 0.545 months and former-current 0.552 months.
- feature_015=squamous was unfavorable versus adenocarcinoma: -0.857 months unadjusted (p<1e-300) and -0.723 months adjusted (p<1e-300).
- feature_036 showed a graded adverse pattern versus level 0: level 1 -1.141 months and level 2 -2.175 months unadjusted; adjusted coefficients were -1.147 and -2.178 months.
- feature_050 was tested as a candidate continuous factor but was not supported: 0.014 months per SD unadjusted (p=0.157) and 0.001 months per SD adjusted (p=0.677).

Several additional binary and continuous features were explored; some remained independent after adjustment while others attenuated. The strongest binary findings explored in iterations 6-10 were feature_001 (-1.438 months unadjusted, adjusted -1.417 months), feature_042 (-0.921 months unadjusted, adjusted -0.912 months), feature_010 (0.782 months unadjusted, adjusted 0.892 months), feature_057 (-0.810 months unadjusted, adjusted -0.028 months), feature_009 (0.322 months unadjusted, adjusted 0.323 months).
The additional continuous findings explored in iterations 11-14 were feature_004 (-0.284 months per SD unadjusted, adjusted -0.283 months per SD), feature_056 (0.221 months per SD unadjusted, adjusted 0.232 months per SD), feature_051 (-0.041 months per SD unadjusted, adjusted -0.036 months per SD), feature_013 (0.022 months per SD unadjusted, adjusted 0.005 months per SD).

Subgroup and interaction findings:
The strongest binary-binary interactions tested in iterations 15-19 were feature_010:feature_009 2.493 months (p<1e-300); feature_010:feature_037 -1.630 months (p<1e-300); feature_009:feature_037 -0.577 months (p<1e-300); feature_010:feature_057 -0.830 months (p<1e-300); feature_010:feature_029 -0.739 months (p<1e-300). Positive coefficients mean the joint subgroup did better than expected from adding the two main effects; negative coefficients mean worse than additivity.
The strongest continuous-binary interactions tested in iterations 20-23 were feature_041 by feature_001 -0.139 months per SD (p<1e-300); feature_041 by feature_042 -0.143 months per SD (p<1e-300); feature_041 by feature_010 0.082 months per SD (p=5.81e-8); feature_041 by feature_028 -0.043 months per SD (p=1.44e-4).

The full multivariable feature model explained R-squared 0.894 of pfs_months variation. Several hypotheses were supported after adjustment, especially feature_041, feature_025, feature_015, feature_036, and the strongest binary features. Feature_050 and the deliberate negative-control style hypothesis in iteration 25 for feature_065 were not supported, with small nonsignificant unadjusted and adjusted effects.

Because feature names are opaque, these results should be interpreted as treatment/biomarker/clinical-feature associations rather than causal effects. The strongest conclusion is that pfs_months in this cohort is heterogeneous: baseline-like variables, categorical clinical strata, multiple binary markers, and specific interactions each contribute measurable differences in progression-free survival.

 succeeded in 1327ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc analysis summary

I analyzed 50,000 records with outcome pfs_months (mean 3.432 months, SD 2.233). Features are de-identified, so conclusions are association patterns rather than causal clinical claims.

Main effects:
- feature_041 was the dominant continuous association: each 1-unit increase corresponded to 0.1699 more months of pfs_months (p<1e-300), and this persisted after adjustment with coefficient 0.1684.
- feature_036 showed strong heterogeneity. feature_036=0 had 1.3797 higher months than all other values, while feature_036=2 had -1.5048 lower months. In the adjusted model, feature_036=0 remained positive (1.1467) and feature_036=2 remained negative (-1.0297).
- Binary/categorical adverse associations included feature_001=1 (-1.4375 months), feature_015=squamous (-0.8569 months), feature_042=1 (-0.9207 months), and feature_025=current (-0.6342 months). These remained directionally strong after adjustment except that feature_025=never did not remain independently beneficial.
- Favorable univariable associations included feature_010=1 (0.7815 months), feature_009=1 (0.322 months), feature_056 (0.4411 months per unit), and feature_066=1 (0.1889 months). feature_066 disappeared after adjustment (adjusted coefficient -0.0007, p=0.9491), suggesting confounding by stronger features.
- Some initially significant adverse signals also did not survive adjustment: feature_057=1 adjusted coefficient -0.0276 (p=0.06987) and feature_028=1 adjusted coefficient -0.0054 (p=0.4711). feature_051 retained a small independent negative slope (-0.000446 months per unit).

Interaction and subgroup patterns:
- The largest binary interaction was feature_010=1 with feature_009=1: the interaction coefficient was 2.5577 months (p<1e-300), indicating more favorable pfs_months when both indicators are present than expected additively.
- feature_037=1 attenuated favorable associations: feature_037=1 x feature_010=1 was -1.6941 months and feature_037=1 x feature_009=1 was -0.5622 months, both highly significant.
- feature_057=1 marked negative subgroup heterogeneity, with negative interactions for feature_025=current x feature_057=1 (-1.0453) and feature_010=1 x feature_057=1 (-1.2096).
- The feature_041 slope varied by subgroup: it was stronger in feature_036=0 (interaction 0.0144), weaker in feature_036=2 (-0.0276), weaker in feature_015=squamous (-0.0118), and weaker in feature_001=1 (-0.0126).

Refuted or weak hypotheses:
- feature_021 showed a small negative slope but was not significant (-0.001697 months per unit, p=0.1123).
- feature_048=1 and feature_050 were weak/non-significant in univariable screening (p=0.1387 and p=0.1571, respectively).

Overall conclusion: pfs_months in this cohort is strongly structured by a small set of opaque features, especially feature_041, feature_036, feature_001, feature_015, feature_025=current, feature_042, feature_010, feature_056, feature_004, and feature_009. Several apparent univariable signals are explained by these dominant features, while interactions involving feature_010, feature_009, feature_037, feature_057, feature_036, feature_015, and feature_001 show meaningful subgroup heterogeneity.

